# Settings, Theme, Accessibility, and i18n

- Theme changes must apply across the full app, not just the settings screen.
- Default theme and language to device preferences on first run, then persist user overrides locally on-device.
- Keep settings and profile data read-only until authentication, verification, and account-type-aware edit flows are designed for both auditor and manager users.
- Avoid browser-centric wording in mobile comments and docs; describe storage as device-local or app-local.
- Accessibility work should prioritize real field conditions: high contrast, readable typography, larger text, and low-friction controls in bright or dark environments.
- Add specialized typography options only when they integrate cleanly with the global design system and remain readable across screens.
- Use i18n for user-facing chrome, settings copy, and status/error messaging; avoid hardcoding new strings directly in screens.
- Keep theme and accessibility state centralized in the design system and preferences store rather than scattered screen overrides.
- Add controls only when they are understandable, global, and supportable long-term.
